92 /**
93 @defgroup Instantiators Instantiator functions
94
95 The Instantiator functions are used to call constructors and `operator new`
96 on classes that implement SQL functions, basically, even though they don't
97 have to be functions. This pattern has to be used because of the
98 following reasons:
99
100 - The parser produces PT_item_list objects of all argument lists, while the
101 Item_func subclasses use overloaded constructors,
102 e.g. Item_xxx_func(Item*), Item_xxx_func(Item*, Item*), etc.
103
104 - We need to map parser tokens to classes and we don't have reflection.
105
106 Because partial template specialization is used, the functions are
107 implemented as class templates rather that functions templates.
108
109 Functions objects that can be created simply by calling the constructor of
110 their respective Item_func class need only instantiate the first template
111 below. Some functions do some special tricks before creating the function
112 object, and in that case they need their own Instantiator. See for instance
113 Bin_instantiator or Oct_instantiator here below for how to do that.
114
115 Keeping the templates in anonymous namespaces enables the compiler to inline
116 more and hence keeps the generated code leaner.
117
118 @{
119 */
120
121 /**
122 We use this to declare that a function takes an infinite number of
123 arguments. The cryptic construction below gives us the greatest number that
124 the return type of PT_item_list::elements() can take.
125
126 @see Function_factory::create_func()
127 */
128 constexpr auto MAX_ARGLIST_SIZE =
129 std::numeric_limits<decltype(PT_item_list().elements())>::max();
130

133

138 general case.
139

141 general case.
142 */

1281 This also instantiates the Function_factory and Instantiator templates.
1282
1283 @param F The Item_func that the factory should make.
1284 @param N Number of arguments that the function accepts.
1285 */
1286 #define SQL_FN_LIST(F, N) \
1287 &Function_factory<List_instantiator<F, N>>::s_singleton
1288
1289 /**
1290 Use this macro if you want to instantiate the Item_func object like
1291 `Item_func_xxx::Item_func_xxx(thd, pos, item_list)`
1292
1293 This also instantiates the Function_factory and Instantiator templates.
1294
1295 @param F The Item_func that the factory should make.
1296 @param MIN Number of arguments that the function accepts.
1297 @param MAX Number of arguments that the function accepts.
1298 */
1299 #define SQL_FN_V_LIST_THD(F, MIN, MAX) \
1300 &Function_factory<List_instantiator_with_thd<F, MIN, MAX>>::s_singleton
1301
1302 /**
1303 Just like SQL_FN_V_THD, but enforces a check that the argument count is odd.
1304 */
1305 #define SQL_FN_ODD(F, MIN, MAX) \

1307 List_instantiator_with_thd<F, MIN, MAX>>::s_singleton
1308

1310 Just like SQL_FN_V_THD, but enforces a check that the argument count is even.
1311 */
1312 #define SQL_FN_EVEN(F, MIN, MAX) \
1313 &Even_argcount_function_factory< \
1314 List_instantiator_with_thd<F, MIN, MAX>>::s_singleton
1315

1343 #define SQL_FN_LIST_INTERNAL(F, N) \

1359 MAINTAINER:
1360 - Keep sorted for human lookup. At runtime, a hash table is used.
1361 - do **NOT** conditionally (\#ifdef, \#ifndef) define a function *NAME*:
1362 doing so will cause user code that works against a `--without-XYZ` binary
1363 to fail with name collisions against a `--with-XYZ` binary.
1364 - keep 1 line per entry, it makes `grep | sort` easier
1365 - Use uppercase (tokens are converted to uppercase before lookup.)

1367 This can't be constexpr because
1368 - Sun Studio does not allow the Create_func pointer to be constexpr.
